## 0.3.0 — USN Journal Support (SHIPPED)

Shipped in v0.3.0. Three APIs:
- `MftVolume.QueryUsnJournal()` — get current journal cursor
- `MftVolume.ReadUsnJournal(cursor)` — batch catch-up read
- `MftVolume.WatchUsnJournal(cursor, cancellationToken)` — live IAsyncEnumerable event stream
- `FileAttributes` sourced from `$STANDARD_INFORMATION` (preferred) with `$FILE_NAME` fallback

## Native C++ Cleanup (dllmain.cpp)

- **Parallelize path resolution**: The post-parse path resolution loop (line ~1272) is serial despite being trivially parallelizable — each `ResolvePath` call does read-only access to `PathLookup` and writes to independent output slots. Could use the same thread pool pattern as fixup+parse.
- **Deduplicate ProcessRecordBatch / ProcessRecordSlice**: These share ~60 lines of nearly identical record-scanning logic. The single-threaded path (numThreads == 1) could use `ProcessRecordSlice` with a single slice, eliminating `ProcessRecordBatch` entirely.
- **Optimize ResolvePath cycle detection**: Uses O(n^2) linear scan over a `visited[128]` array. A simple bitmask or hash set would be O(1) per check. At millions of records this adds up.
- **PathLookup memory**: `namePoolCapacity = totalRecords * 32` over-allocates (~512 MB at 8M records). Average filename is ~12-15 chars; `totalRecords * 20` would be safer. Also, `storeName` silently drops names when the pool is exhausted — should at least set an error flag.

## Review Follow-Ups

- Decide whether `MFTLib` should expose a higher-level scan-result contract for app-to-helper transport.
  Address by evaluating whether downstream apps should keep custom text formats for elevated scans or share a library-owned record serializer.

- Optional: make benchmark environment failures explicit instead of silently printing `Unknown`.
  Address by logging the WMI/CIM exception message or HRESULT in the benchmark header when system info queries fail.

## Test Infrastructure

- **Admin test runs hang on exit (recurring).** When `run-coverage.ps1` (full mode) or `native-coverage.ps1` is launched elevated via UAC, the elevated process intermittently fails to exit cleanly after `dotnet test` reports all tests passed — the parent shell sits indefinitely waiting on `Start-Process -Wait`. Same symptom appears with both `Microsoft.CodeCoverage.Console collect` (native script) and the plain coverlet path (managed script). Suspects to investigate:
  - `WatchUsnJournal_*` admin tests use `CancelIoEx` to unblock a kernel wait — possible the cancel races with process teardown and leaves a worker thread in a non-signaled wait, blocking the runtime's exit. Worth checking with `procdump -ma` on a hung session to see what threads are alive.
  - `dotnet test` host process (`testhost.dll`) running under instrumentation may not flush the coverage file before the parent reaps it — could be the instrumentation harness, not the tests themselves.
  - A timeout wrapper around the elevated invocation (e.g. `Start-Process` with a watchdog that issues `taskkill /T` after N minutes past the last log line) would at least prevent the session from blocking forever.
  - Long-term: split admin-only tests into a separate test project so the non-admin run stays the default and elevated runs can be opted into with a known-stable test set.
